doc.title: Sweden: September Cut Remains Off Balance In Aflation Should Fall Further in August

passages.text: BOTTOM LINE: Activity data out of Sweden over the past week has been mostly on the brighter side, but we think is still consistent with more easing ahead from the Riksbank. The final Q2 GDP print of \(0.5\%\) qoq still fell short of the Riksbank's \(0.9\%\) qoq expectations, and was partly driven by inventory accumulation. Retail sales and consumer confidence improved but remain at historically low levels. Besides, the latest seasonally adjusted LFS unemployment rate stood at \(8.9\%\) in July, notably higher than the Riksbank's latest forecast. At the same time, we expect CPIF to be unchanged at \(3.0\%\) yoy, and CPIF ex. energy to fall to \(2.9\%\) yoy in August, still somewhat above the Riksbank's June projections but beginning to unwind the summer- related strength. As the August meeting minutes point to Riksbank's Executive Board members' openness to lowering rates further if the inflation acceleration proves temporary, we stick with our baseline view of a 25bp cut to \(1.75\%\) in September, conditional on inflation developing in line with our expectations.
Retail Sales (Jul): \(0.3\%\) , last: \(2.6\%\) (revised from \(2.5\%\) ), all %mom
NIER Consumer Confidence (Aug): 91.1, last: 90.8 (revised from 90.7)

1. Activity data out of Sweden over the past week has been mostly on the brighter side, but we think is still consistent with more easing ahead from the Riksbank. First, the final Q2 GDP print came in at \(0.5\%\) qoq, higher than the flash estimate of \(0.1\%\) qoq and our expectations, but still notably below the Riksbank's projection of \(0.9\%\) qoq. While household consumption grew by \(0.4\%\) qoq and gross investment rebounded after a weak Q1, a big uptick in inventories contributed notably to the upside surprise, pointing to some stock build-up in the economy. Incorporating the Q2 final release, our forecast for 2025 annual growth now stands at \(1.1\%\) , still notably below our estimate of potential. Second, retail sales remained broadly flat in July, printing at \(0.3\%\) mom, with the level still depressed from a historically weak May print of \(-4.3\%\) mom. Consumer confidence in the NIER survey improved for the fourth month in a row in August, but saw only a modest increase to 91.1. The economic tendency indicator also saw an uptick in August to 96.0. That said, the levels of both remain below the long-run mean. Besides, the latest seasonally
adjusted LFS unemployment rate stood at \(8.9\%\) in July, notably higher than the Riksbank's latest forecast.

2. At the same time, while July inflation details pointed to a slight moderation in the upside surprise seen in June, core inflation still stood at \(3.15\% \text{yo} y\) -0.3pp above the Riksbank's expectations and slightly firmer than our forecast of \(3.1\% \text{yo} y\) . For August, we expect CPIF to be unchanged at \(3.0\% \text{yo} y\) , and CPIF ex. energy to come down to \(2.9\% \text{yo} y\) (from \(3.15\% \text{yo} y\) in July), both below consensus of \(3.2\% \text{yo} y\) and \(3.0\% \text{yo} y\) , respectively, but still above the Riksbank's June projections (of \(2.7\% \text{yo} y\) for both). We see services decelerating quite notably on the month, driven by the beginning of an unwind in the summer-related strength in airfares (- \(25\% \text{mm} \text{nsa}\) ), package holidays (- \(20\% \text{mm} \text{nsa}\) ), and other transportation services (- \(4\% \text{mm} \text{nsa}\) ). We expect goods inflation to rebound to \(0.2\% \text{mm} \text{nsa}\) after a - \(0.3\% \text{mm} \text{prin}\) t in July, and see some uncertainty around electricity price dynamics.

3. The August meeting minutes point to Riksbank's Executive Board members' openness to lowering rates further if the inflation acceleration proves temporary. While all members shared an assessment that the recovery is proceeding slower than expected and the labour market remains weak, the recent spike in inflation caused more concern for some than for others. Deputy Governor Seim, for example, cautioned that even though she "shared the assessment that inflation is temporarily high," she feared "it may surprise on the upside." At the same time, Deputy Governor Jansson acknowledged that "if one only looks at economic activity, then it would probably be desirable to have an interest-rate cut at the August meeting," as opposed to Governor Thedeen, who sounded somewhat cautious during the press conference, saying that, if not for its broader mandate, the Riksbank "may have had to consider a hike".

4. Riksbank officials have again emphasised benign inflation as a necessary condition for further easing. While we expect inflation to unwind the June uptick in the upcoming months, starting as early as the August print, and undershoot the target in 2026, uncertainty is still high. While the activity data starts to look slightly better, the economy remains weak, the labour market is subdued, and there is still uncertainty over whether trade tensions could result in more growth weakness ahead. We thus stick with our baseline forecast of a 25bp cut to \(1.75\%\) in September, conditional on inflation developing in line with our expectations.
Exhibit 1: Labour Market Remains Subdued and Inflation Is Set to Decelerate
Source:Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research,Haver Analytics,Riksbank
